The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:

```csharp
public interface IFileSystem
{
    string ReadAllText(string path);
    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);
    bool DirectoryExists(string path);
}

public class PhysicalFileSystem : IFileSystem
{
    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);
    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);
    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

Then inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling `File`/`Directory` directly. In tests, you can mock it or use a simple in-memory implementation.

**Alternatively**, use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a `MockFileSystem` for testing:

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # for tests
```

```csharp
// Production code — inject IFileSystem
public class MyService(IFileSystem fs)
{
    public string Load(string path) => fs.File.ReadAllText(path);
}

// Test code
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddFile("/data.txt", new MockFileData("hello"));
var svc = new MyService(mockFs);
Assert.Equal("hello", svc.Load("/data.txt"));
```

**TL;DR**: Use `System.IO.Abstractions` if you want a battle-tested solution. Roll your own thin interface if you only need a few methods and want zero dependencies.
